e period. From John Cage to Allan Kaprow, Mark Rothko to Ludwig Wittgenstein, Antin takes the reader on an idiosyncratic, personal journey through twentieth-century culture with his trademark antiformalist panache—one thatwill be welcomed by any fan of this consummate trailblazer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican poetryxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArt criticismxUnited States. 0aArt criticismzUnited States. 0aArt, Americanx20th century. 0aArt, Americany20th century. 0aExperimental poetryxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aExperimental poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226923321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226923321.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles